posts.cooked: I am trying to print on Ender S3. The model is large because it is for the other tools I use for the printer. It uses a lot of filament and time. Is there something I can do to change either in onshape, the slicer, or the printer to make it use less filament

posts.name: Thomas Gilmore
posts.cooked: Without knowing what the model is, some options are to increase the layer height or decrease the infill density in the slicer. Doing this will decrease the strength of the product, so it may not be ideal in certain scenarios.

posts.name: chrisrin
posts.cooked: Often, one can use a larger nozzle (like 0.6mm instead of the default 0.4mm) in order to print functional parts faster. Just remember to update the printer configuration in your slicer if you do that. Beyond that, look at your slicer settings and select a draft/coarser quality option rather that a finer quality option on parts that have simpler geometry.
what can i do if i only have one nozzle

posts.name: chrisrin
posts.cooked:
Few things:

Even if you just have one nozzle and it is 0.4mm (the size 3D printers usually have when new), you can select draft/coarse in your slicer to print things faster, and for many functional parts this will be fine. If any of the parts you’re printing are very detailed, then the “normal” quality setting is probably better.

There are tons of Youtube videos out there, and probably even some for your specific printer. It’s an easy way to learn.

If you have only a single nozzle, then you will want to buy some more because they can wear out, plus as explained there are uses for differerent sizes. There are other supplies as well that you may need. I bet there are articles or videos out there with recommendations.

I hope you have fun getting to know your printer! I’ve had fun the past few years tinkering with mine.

posts.name: Nyx
posts.cooked:
In order of how each setting affects print time (same model, same amount of materials): Layer height - how many times the printer has to go over each layer. Going from 0.1mm to 0.2mm will approximately halve print time. Nozzle size - larger nozzles move material faster, increases strength slightly, sometimes can use more material, but also reduces resolution. Infill settings - Especially at higher infills between about 30 and 80% changing the infill pattern can massively influence the amount of time. Supports - You won’t need them for this print, but using better supports than what many slicers provide (especially cura based and MB print) can and will massively reduce effort and material used in prints.

I would need to know more about the slicer and certain settings to be able to give you much more useful information for infill print reduction times.

Another thing you could do, assuming you don’t need solid sides (or only need solid sides on one edge), is to simply cut out a bunch of the material - this has a habit of saving a lot of material and time without compromising much strength.

Personally, I would arrange to make this with laser cut parts (or waterjet if you have that available, I guess) - it’s just a box, and you can make that really easily with a laser cutter and some practical design. 3D printers are perfect for extremely weird geometry that doesn’t involve flat parts and can’t really be made on a CNC.

If it’s an ender, I’d also recommend using a brim instead of a raft - the things have pretty good bed adhesion a lot of the time.

posts.name: Thomas Gilmore
posts.cooked: I would definitely use a decreased infill density for a majority of the prints. Depending on what slicer you use, you should be able to select specific areas of the part to have higher or lower density. Here’s a link to a video that shows how to do it in Cura.
